1 burden associated with child abuse and neglect estimated to be
2 $2,600,000,000 in Hawaii. The legislature additionally finds
3 that fifty-eight per cent of Hawaii children live in families
4 made vulnerable by adverse childhood experiences, which include
5 family violence, substance abuse, untreated family mental health
6 issues, divorce, or incarceration.
7 The legislature additionally finds that peer-to-peer
8 support programs provide people with an instant and
9 cost-effective safety net. Parents and caregivers have a place
10 where they can learn, get screening and referrals, share
11 resources, and build their self-confidence. The goal of these
12 programs is to keep parents and children together, strengthen
13 and grow community support and services, and increase the sense
14 of hope and self-assurance amongst parents and caregivers of
15 young children. Peer-to-peer support programs have also proven
16 to be effective in reducing negative parenting practices,
17 connecting victims of intimate partner violence to appropriate
18 support, and encouraging completion of substance use disorder
19 programs.
20 The legislature notes that investing early in peer-to-peer
21 support programs can save millions of taxpayer dollars in
